---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How do I know when my pool actually needs resurfacing?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Five signs that mean it is time, not next year. Visible cracking or crazing across larger areas of the interior (small spots are normal). Rough patches that catch your feet — the surface aggregate has worn through to the base. Persistent staining that no amount of chemical treatment touches. Plaster blistering or hollow patches that sound different when you tap them. And water loss above 25mm per week with no plumbing leak detected. Pebble finishes typically last 12–18 years. Quartz lasts 15–20. Plaster lasts 8–12. Fully tiled interiors last 25–30 if the grout is maintained. Many Berwick 1980s and 1990s pools are well overdue." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What does each finish cost per square metre for resurfacing?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Marble-sand plaster is the budget option at $55–$80 per square metre supplied and applied — 8–12 year life. Standard pebblecrete sits at $90–$140 per square metre — 12–18 year life. Premium quartz blends like StoneScapes or PebbleSheen are $130–$210 per square metre — 15–20 year life with a much finer texture underfoot. Glass-bead pebble is $170–$240 per square metre — the luminous shimmer finish, premium look. Full porcelain or glass mosaic tile retiling is $280–$550+ per square metre depending on the tile — 25–30 year life if grout is maintained. A standard 8 × 4m pool has roughly 60–70 square metres of interior surface to cover." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can you just paint over the existing surface instead of resurfacing?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Two-pack epoxy pool paint exists and we will apply it if that is what you want, but be clear-eyed about what you are getting. Lifespan is 3–7 years before another recoat — sometimes shorter on heavily-used pools. Cost is $20–$35 per square metre. It is a stopgap, not a renovation. We use it for clients selling within 2–3 years where a fresh look matters more than long-term durability, and for older pools where the owner wants one more season of life before a proper resurface. We do not recommend it as a long-term solution and we will say so before we quote." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do I have to empty the pool, and what happens to the water?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes. Resurfacing requires the pool be drained, the existing surface keyed (acid-etched, sandblasted or chipped depending on what is going over the top), and a clean substrate prepared before the new finish goes on. Casey reactive-clay sites need careful timing on the drain — an empty pool sitting through a wet winter can move. We do drains in stable weather windows, complete prep within 5–7 days, apply the finish within another 3–5 days, and refill on day 10–14. The water itself: most owners chemically neutralise it and discharge to stormwater under the Yarra Valley Water trade-waste guidelines. We can do this for you or you can DIY with a $40 neutralising kit." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Will the equipment also need replacing while the pool is empty?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Resurfacing is the cheapest time to upgrade equipment because the pool is already offline. We usually recommend three checks. Pump — if it is single-speed and over 10 years old, switch to a variable-speed pump now and recover the cost in pumping electricity within 24 months. Salt chlorinator cell — if the cell is over 6 years old it is at end of life regardless of whether it is still producing chlorine. Filter — cartridge filters last 8–12 years, sand filters 12–15. If the surface is being redone, do the equipment audit at the same time and you avoid two separate downtimes." }
    }
  ]
};
---
<Layout
  title="Pool Resurfacing Berwick — Pebble, Quartz, Tile Options 2026 | Berwick Pools"
  description="Pool resurfacing in Berwick — pebble vs quartz vs tile vs paint compared. Cost per square metre, lifespan, feel underfoot. SPASA Victoria member, full equipment audit included."
  canonical="https://berwickpools.com.au/pool-resurfacing-berwick/">
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />
  </Fragment>

  <section class="hero">
    <div class="hero-inner">
      <span class="hero-eyebrow">For owners of 1980s–2000s Berwick pool stock</span>
      <h1>Pool resurfacing in Berwick — <span class="accent">pebble, quartz, tile and what each one really feels like</span>.</h1>
      <p class="hero-sub">
        A clear-eyed comparison of the 2026 resurfacing options for the wave of 25 to
        45-year-old pools across Berwick, Narre Warren and Endeavour Hills. Feel
        underfoot, lifespan, cost per square metre, and what is worth doing while the
        pool is already empty.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a class="btn btn-primary" href="tel:+61390030108">&#9742; Call (03) 9003 0108</a>
        <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/quote/">Book a site visit</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <h2>The ageing-pool wave in Berwick.</h2>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <p>
          A large slice of Berwick’s residential pool stock was built between 1985 and
          2005 — the great suburban pool boom of late-century Melbourne. The shells
          are mostly still excellent (a properly built concrete shell will outlast a
          generation of owners), but the interior finishes have aged out. We are
          getting two or three resurfacing enquiries a week from owners who have
          inherited a pool with crazed pebble, blistered plaster, or rough patches
          that grab toes.
        </p>
        <p>
          Resurfacing is not the same conversation as a new build. The decisions are
          smaller, the timeline is shorter (usually 10–14 days from drain to fill),
          and the cost is a fraction of replacement. But the choice of finish locks
          in another 12–25 years of look-and-feel for the pool, so it is worth the
          time to compare properly.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">The five real options on the table in 2026.</h3>
        <p>
          We will go through these in price order, from budget to premium. The right
          choice depends as much on how long you plan to own the house as on budget.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Two-pack epoxy paint — $20–$35/m², 3–7 year life.</strong> The stopgap. Fast, cheap, and a clean fresh look — but you are signing up for another recoat in less than a decade. We do this for short-hold properties and pre-sale refreshes only.</li>
          <li><strong>Marble-sand plaster — $55–$80/m², 8–12 year life.</strong> The traditional plaster finish. Smooth, classic, and historically the default. Less popular now because pebblecrete outlasts it for not much more money — but still the right answer if you are restoring an older pool to original spec.</li>
          <li><strong>Pebblecrete — $90–$140/m², 12–18 year life.</strong> The workhorse of the modern Australian pool. Hard-wearing, slip-resistant, natural-looking, dozens of colour blends. The most common choice for resurfacing in Berwick and the City of Casey.</li>
          <li><strong>Quartz blends (StoneScapes, PebbleSheen, Diamond Brite) — $130–$210/m², 15–20 year life.</strong> A finer aggregate than pebblecrete with a smoother feel underfoot. The premium-mid tier. Particularly popular for plunge pools and spas where bare-feet comfort matters.</li>
          <li><strong>Glass-bead pebble — $170–$240/m², 15–20 year life.</strong> Fully crushed glass aggregate that shimmers and changes colour with the light. The “Mediterranean luminous” aesthetic — increasingly popular in newer Officer and Clyde North builds.</li>
          <li><strong>Full porcelain or glass mosaic tile — $280–$550+/m², 25–30 year life.</strong> The forever finish. Highest cost, longest life, premium feel. The right answer if you are planning to own the house for the next 20+ years.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Feel underfoot — the thing the brochure does not tell you.</h3>
        <p>
          Spend 15 minutes at our office or a recent project and we will let you walk
          on samples of every finish with bare feet. The differences are real and
          they matter for daily use.
        </p>
        <p>
          Pebblecrete has visible aggregate — it is textured, slip-resistant, and
          most people describe it as “solid” underfoot. It can feel scratchy after a
          long swim if the aggregate blend is coarse. Quartz feels noticeably
          smoother — like fine sandpaper rather than gravel. Glass-bead is the
          smoothest of the aggregate finishes and feels almost slippery in places
          (which is why we recommend a textured coping band around the steps). Full
          tile is dead-smooth and gorgeous but you do need to think about non-slip
          treatments on the steps and on the shallow ledge.
        </p>
        <p>
          If you have kids who swim daily and run around the edge, the slight
          slip-resistance of pebblecrete is genuinely worth something. If the pool is
          mostly adult use with bare feet, quartz or glass-bead is more comfortable.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">What is worth doing while the pool is empty.</h3>
        <p>
          The 10–14 day window when the pool is drained is the cheapest time you
          will ever have to address other things. Three items we routinely bundle:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Equipment audit.</strong> If the pump is single-speed and over 10 years old, switching to a variable-speed pump now recovers its cost in pumping electricity within 24 months — and we are already on site.</li>
          <li><strong>Waterline tile band.</strong> If the existing waterline tile is grouted-out, stained, or just out of fashion, redoing it while the surface is being prepared adds $1,200–$3,000 to the job. Done separately later it costs nearly double.</li>
          <li><strong>Pool light upgrade.</strong> Old halogen pool lights can be swapped to LED with a colour-change controller for $800–$1,800 while the pool is empty. After refill you cannot access the niche without draining again.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Timing the drain to Casey weather.</h3>
        <p>
          On reactive-clay sites an empty pool is a temporary structural risk. With
          no water weight inside, the surrounding clay can press inward, and on
          high-water-table blocks the hydrostatic pressure from groundwater can lift
          the shell. Neither is common, but both are real. We schedule drains for
          dry windows — typically March–May and September–November — and we work
          fast. Average drain-to-fill is 10–14 days; we have done resurfaces in 8
          when the weather cooperated.
        </p>
        <p>
          Older pools with no hydrostatic relief valve are higher risk in winter.
          Part of the prep on those pools is installing one before the drain — a
          $400 inclusion that prevents a $15,000 problem.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
